occurrences.line_text: Are washt away quite from their memorie.
Sternly stept forth, and raught away his speare,
Or went away sore wounded of his haplesse hand.
For to haue rent his shield and armes away,
Cambello it away before had got:
Leading his friend away, full sorie to his vew.
The prayse of prowesse from them all away.
And brought with her fro[m] thence that goodly belt away.
That able was weake harts away to steale.
That she should surely beare the bell away,
And fell away, as feeling secret blame.
But secretly from thence that night her bore away.
Not farre away, not meete for any guest
Whiles thus they communed, lo farre away
Her ventayle shard away, and thence forth glaunst
Fearing least she your loues away should woo,
And stolne away from her beloued mate,
And through the forrest bore her quite away,
I with that Squire agreede away to flit,
And now he her away with him did beare
But fled away with ghastly dreriment,
But turnd her face, and fled away for euermore.
And threw away, with vow to vse no more,
Hauing espide this Cabin far away,
And haue the sterne remembrance wypt away
And pensiue sorrow pind and wore away,
And flew away, as lightly as the wind:
With ready hand it to haue reft away.
And still from her escaping soft away:
A litle cotage farre away they spide,
And steale away the crowne of their good name;
Shooting forth farre away two flaming streames,
Into the lookers hart, and killeth farre away.
But none of them (so fast away he flew)
I lightly snatcht him vp, and with me bore away.
But haue perforce him hether brought away.
But farre away from these, another sort
And turn'd his face away, as he did stand,
The whilest their eldest brother was away,
Now well away, that I haue doen such wrong,
Then did he cast to steale her thence away,
He wist not how her thence away to bere;
His cleared heart eftsoones away gan chace
Out of their proper places farre away,
Ah woe is me, and well away (quoth hee)
Fro me reft mine away by lawlesse might,
Not so to leaue her, nor away to cast,
So he my loue away with him hath borne,
Nor tooke away his loue, but his owne proper good.
Else he doth hold him backe or beat away.
That sure they ween'd she was escapt away:
But the streame washt away her guilty blood.
He giues to this, from that he takes away.
But he the right from thence did thrust away,
Where they were leading Marinell away,
The glorious picture vanisheth away,
The whiles his guilefull groome was fled away:
The most part of my land hath washt away,
And though my land he first did winne away,
Vnto your part, and pluckt from his away,
A rout of many people farre away;
The badges of reproch, he threw away,
Her from the quarrey he away doth driue,
When thus the field was voided all away,
Halfe of her shield he shared quite away,
That they were fayne to let him scape away,
Not farre away, but little wide by West,
And talk't of pleasant things, the night away to weare.
Bad doe away the dampe of drouzie sleepe,
And therefore loth to loose her right away,
Who still from him as fast away did flie,
From whom she earst so fast away did flie;
That O ye heauens defend, and turne away
So fast away, that ere his readie speare
And with their ryder ranne perforce away:
He vp did take, and with him brought away,
With her, to see her Ladie thence no farre away.
Which wonned in a rocke not farre away,
To turne her eyes from his intent away:
Ran with her fast away vnto his mew,
He threw his burden downe, and fast away did fly.
And prickt him so, that he away it threw.
Then gan it runne away incontinent,
Seeking to driue away deepe rooted dreede,
As fast as feete could carry them away;
And entraunce wonne. Streight th'other fled away,
Durst not abide, but fled away for feare,
That two more of his armes did fall away,
Her Lions clawes he from her feete away did wipe.
And farre away, amid their rakehell bands,
And forced him to throw it quite away,
Like scattred chaffe, the which the wind away doth fan.
By open force to fetch her quite away:
So bore her quite away, nor well nor ill apayd.
Did win the shore, whence he them chast away,
By those, which earst did fly away for feare
So sounded the retraite, and drew his folke away.
He through occasion called was away,
And gracious speach, did steale mens hearts away.
But they that Ladies lockes doe shaue away,
With his long taile the bryzes brush away.
Therefore he wild her doe away all dread;
But put away proud looke, and vsage sterne,
And both the eyes did steale the hart away.
A tall young man from thence not farre away,
Thought best away me to remoue somewhere
Fain'd her to frolicke, and to put away
And droue away the stound, which mortally attacht him.
And by outragious force away did beare:
And in his wide great mouth away her bare,
His weapons soone from him he threw away,
He quite forsooke, and fled himselfe away for feare.
From his soft eyes the teares he wypt away,
Sir Calepine himselfe away had hidden it.
Reuiued was, and sad dispaire away did cast.
Hath you thus long away from me bereft?
And in all battels bore away the baies.
And therefore lightly bad him packe away,
Who flying still did ward, and warding fly away.
Those goodly armes, he them away did giue
Thence he him brought away, and vp conuayd
The gentle Prince not farre away they spyde,
Thence passing forth, not farre away he found,
Or their owne guilt, they were away conuayd.
And fled away with all the speede she mought,
With those two Carles, fled fast away, afeard
Ne any will had thence to moue away,
And the fayre mayd the table ta'ne away,
Vnto my Lambes, and him dislodge away;
Of his rich mould, did thrust it farre away,
Watching to driue the rauenous Wolfe away,
Keeping all noysome things away from it,
The vanisht all away out of his sight,
But why when I them saw, fled they away from me?
That thence, he had no will away to fare,
Through cowherd feare he fled away as fast,
And droue away their flocks, with other much disorder.
And all his people captiue led away;
Mongst which this lucklesse mayd away was lad,
And carried captiue by those theeues away;
And flyes away as fast as he can hye,
And his Loue reft away, he wexed wood,
Whose whelpes are stolne away, she being otherwhere.
Ah well away (sayd he then sighing sore)
Hath wrought this wicked deed: doe feare away, and tell.
They chaunst, vpon an hill not farre away,
Now all vnwares, and take the spoyle away;
So droue them all away, and his loue with him bore.
But seeing Calidore, away he flew,
Was warie wise, and closely did awayt
Forgets with warie ward them to awayt,
And for your ruine at the last awayt.
But drew him on with hope, fit leasure to awayt.
Yet to awayt fit time she weened best,
They in awayt would closely him ensnarle,
He watcht in close awayt with weapons prest,
The Briton Prince him readie did awayte,
With that the foole, which did that end awayte,
And them awayted there a certaine space,
Awayted there for Britomarts returne,
Where groomes awayted her to haue vndrest.
The Redcrosse knight awaytes,
Awayting to entrap the warelesse wight,
The Sarazin, awayting for some spoile.
But her fierce seruant full of kingly awe
Held vertue for it selfe in soueraine awe:
He thought her to compell by crueltie and awe.
And tost the Paynim, without feare or awe;
His name was Awe; by whom they passing in
Bate somewhat of that Maiestie and awe,
Glad to be quit from that proud Tyrants awe,
Gan stoupe, and falling downe with humble awe,
Without regard of pitty or of awe.
And peoples harts with awfull terrour tye,
For with dredd Maiestie, and awfull ire,
And awfull terror deepe into him strooke,
And vse of awfull Maiestie remoue:
That furthest Nations filles with awfull dread,
That euen wilde beasts did feare his awfull sight,
All ouergrowne with haire, that could awhape
That any man would nigh awhaped make.
The which to heare, vouchsafe, O dearest dred a-while.
There she awhile him stayes, him selfe to rest,
Thus they awhile with court and goodly game,
Where both awhile would couered remaine,
With that the Prophet still awhile did stay,
All which his sonne Careticus awhile
Stared on her awhile, as one astound,
But past awhile, when she fit season saw
That each awhile lay like a sencelesse corse.
Then sighing soft awhile, at last she thus:
And fruitfull apples to haue borne awhile,
Shall breath it selfe awhile, after so long a went.
T'alight, and rest their wearie limbs awhile.
There to their fortune leaue we them awhile,
That hauing there their wounds awhile redrest,
There they awhile some gracious speaches spent,
Awhile on her they greedily did gaze,
Tho when the shepheard breathed had awhile,
But after griefe awhile had had his course,
Ne from his currish will awhit reclame.
Giue leaue awhyle, good father, in this shore
Swift Awniduff, which of the English man
When I awoke, and found her place deuoyd,
The man awoke, and would haue questiond more;
That he awoke out of his idle dreme,
Who long before awoke (for she ful ill
Like one that out of deadly dreame awooke:
Where still he lay, ne out of swoune awooke,
And his embrodered Bonet sat awry;
And wrong redresse in such as wend awry.
And so were realmes and nations run awry.
Like to a rancke of piles, that pitched are awry.
And heau'd his murdrous axe at him with mighty sway.
And with his axe him smote in euill hower,
And with his huge great yron axe gan hew
Eftsoones againe his axe he raught on hie,
And did his yron axe so nimbly wield,
His axe he could not from his shield vndoe.
And with their axes both so sorely bet,
Ay wont in desert darknesse to remaine,
To be the chastest flowre, that ay did spring
Ay me, that is a double death (she said)
Ay me, how many perils doe enfold
Ay wont to laugh, when them I heard to cry,
That ay thereof her babes might sucke their fill;
Or like that pleasaunt Mount, that is for ay
What need of armes, where peace doth ay remaine,
Ay me, deare Lady, which the image art
Was, (ay the while, that he is not so now)
Dye, or thy selfe my captiue yield for ay;
Which she in Stygian lake, ay burning bright,
And my trew liegeman yield thy selfe for ay,
Donwallo dyde (for what may liue for ay?)
Ay caroling of loue and iollity,
Ay ioyning foot to foot, and side to side,
Ay doing things, that to his fame redound,
If ay more goodly creature thou didst see;
She firmely hath emprisoned for ay,
Ay when to him she cryde, to her he turnd,
Ne ought but deare Bisaltis ay could make him glad.
Ay me (quoth she) what wicked destinie?
Ay me (sayd she) and whether shall I goe?
Ay me, that euer guyle in wemen was inuented.
To loue another. Lo then for thine ayd
O heare, how piteous he to you for ayd does call.
Poore prisoners to relieue with gratious ayd,
And widowes ayd, least they should be vndone:
And rushed in on foot to ayd her, ere she dyde.
Gaue him great ayd, and made him more inclind:
Into the lake he lept, his Lord to ayd,
So euill thing to seeke vnto their ayd,
My Lord, my liege, by whose most gratious ayd
Till that the villein comming to their ayd,
The clothes about her round with busie ayd;
No seruice, bu tthy safety and ayd;
Of your gay sonne, that giues ye so good ayd
The wretched man hearing her call for ayd,
For pitie that ye want a fellow for your ayd.
They to his succour ran with readie ayd:
He pricked forth in ayd of Satyran;
To hasten greatly to his parties ayd,
But if few plants preseru'd through heauenly ayd,
And made his Dwarfe, though with vnwilling ayd,
And to those knights, for their so noble ayd,
Assure your selfe, Sir Knight, she shall haue ayd,
Ne powre had to withstand, ne hope of any ayd.
To Fortunes spoile, vnable it to ayd.
And with thy mother milde come to mine ayde:
That promist ayde the tempest to withstand:
Fly to your faith for succour and sure ayde:
Her champion stout, and for to ayde his frend,
And to Diana calling lowd for ayde,
To call them all in order to her ayde,
Ne canst her ayde, ne canst her foe dismay:
Both vnassaylable, gaue him great ayde:
Yet when as foes enforst, or friends sought ayde,
For ayde, against that cruell Tyrants theft,
That Tyrants part, with close or open ayde,
Next that ye Ladies ayde in euery stead and stound.
I should no creature ioyne vnto mine ayde,
Vnto the Knights, and calling oft for ayde;
Which lay thereby (so fortune him did ayde)
Which if they would afford him ayde at need
But Calidore soone comming to her ayde,
Aye me, Deare dame (quoth he) well may I rew
On top whereof aye dwelt the ghastly Owle,
But let me here for aye in peace remaine,
Bynempt a sacred vow, which none should aye releace.
Straunge seemed to the knight, that aye with foe
And all that in the world was aye thought wittily.
And aye the cups their bancks did ouerflow,
And aye betweene the cups, she did prepare
Aye me, how much I feare, least loue it bee;
For who with reason can you aye reproue,
Daughter, I deeme that counsell aye most fit,
And vsd the same in battell aye to beare;
Yet might not do him dye, but aye more fresh
Aye me, (said Paridell) the signes be sad,
For aye the more that she the same reherst,
Aye me (said she) where am I, or with whom?
Aye me to see that gentle maide so tost.
I leaue to you, for aye me to disgrace
And swore to him true fealtie for aye.
Aye me (sayd then Serena sighing sore)
For aye the more, that she did them entreat,
But aye the more he rag'd, the more his powre increast.
For aye in darkenesse, which day light doth shonne:
Were fixed at his backe, to cut his ayerie wayes.
Was from her fled, as flit as ayerie Doue,
With golden aygulets, that glistred bright,
Ran hastily, to weete what did him ayle.
And ayme at him, fell flat to ground for feare,
That knowes her port, and thither sailes by ayme,
To which all men do ayme, rich to be made:
Of her false eyes, that at her hart did ayme,
Ne by inquirie learne, nor ghesse by ayme.
He seekes, of all his drift the aymed end:
Then at the aymed marke, which he had eide:
The quiuering steele his aymed end well knew,
But ere the stroke could seize his aymed place,
With dreadfull weapon aymed at his head;
That ere they come vnto their aymed scope,
But th'other ayming better, did him smite
He making speedy way through spersed ayre,
And fram'd of liquid ayre her tender partes
Through widest ayre making his ydle way,
This Nymph, quite tyr'd with heat of scorching ayre,
With thundring noyse, and all the ayre doth choke,
And scourging th'emptie ayre with his long traine,
That all the ayre with terrour filled wide,
With which whenas him list the ayre to beat,
That all the ayre about with smoke and stench did fill.
Cleare the deawy ayre with springing light,
All suddenly dim woxe the dampish ayre,
The subtile ayre, stouping with all his might,
Perceth the yielding ayre, and doth displace
And with wide wings to beat the buxome ayre,
On whom he got faire Pegasus, that flitteth in the ayre.
Ne into ayre did vanish presently,
And fire deuoure the ayre, and hell them quight,
Great God of men and women, queene of th'ayre,
And one of th'ayre, without or wind, or wether:
Her goodly bow, which paints the liquid ayre;
And lends vnto it leaue the emptie ayre to beat.
To take the ayre, and heare the thrushes song,
Which glyding through the ayre lights all the heauens darke.
Confused, did the ayre with terror fill,
The wicked shaft guyded through th'ayrie wyde,
That deckt the azure field with her faire pouldred skin.
He vp gan lift toward the azure skies,
And through the persant aire shoote forth their azure streames.
And also those which wonne in th'azure sky?
As when two sunnes appeare in the azure skye,
Clad all in gilden armes, with azure band
Halfe dead through feare, her litle babe reuyld,
But thou, sweet Babe, whom frowning froward fate
Als in her lap a louely babe did play
Hard helpe at need. So deare thee babe I bought,
The little babe vp in his armes he hent;
Ah lucklesse babe, borne vnder cruell starre,
The bloudy-handed babe vnto her truth
A gyaunt babe, her selfe for griefe did kill;
Her tender babe, it seeing safe appeare,
Be to the Briton babe, that shalbe borne,
Vp they them tooke, each one a babe vptooke,
Dame Phoebe to a Nymph her babe betooke,
For at that berth another Babe she bore,
And their young bloodie babe to him gan tell;
The litle babe did loudly scrike and squall,
The litle babe, sweet relickes of his pray;
This litle babe, of sweete and louely face,
She gladly did of that same babe accept,
The litle babe, to take thereof a sight.
Whereof king Nine whilome built Babell towre;
With bloud of guiltlesse babes, and innocents trew,
That ay thereof her babes might sucke their fill;
A multitude of babes about her hong,
Babes bloudie hands may not be clensd,
From thence it comes, that this babes bloudy hand
Be but as bugs to fearen babes withall,
Words fearen babes. I meane not thee entreat
As other wemens babes, they sucked vitall blood.
Vnwares had borne two babes, as faire as springing day.
But from her louing side the tender babes to take.
A thousand thousand naked babes attend
These three so noble babes to bring forth at one clap.
Got these three louely babes, that prov'd three cha[m]pions bold.
Bablers of folly, and blazers of crime.
The whiles his babling tongue did yet blaspheme
There was that great proud king of Babylon,
There was the signe of antique Babylon,
But fierce Bacchante seemd too fell and keene;
If Bacchus merry fruit they did inuent,
So soone as Bacchus with the Nymphe does lincke:
Now Bacchus fruit out of the siluer plate
Such first was Bacchus, that with furious might
Of Bacchus Priests her owne deare flesh did teare.
By that same hole an entrance darke and bace
My ragged rimes are all too rude and bace,
But yield his sence to be too blunt and bace,
Had vertue pourd into their waters bace,
And all that else this worlds enclosure bace,
In heauenly spirits to these creatures bace,
Distempred through misrule and passions bace:
But yelling Meawes, with Seagulles hoarse and bace,
That as the one stird vp affections bace,
Certaine sad words, with hollow voice and bace,
But foolish boy, what bootes thy seruice bace
And curteise vse conceiu'd affection bace,
Where when he found it not (for Trompart bace
They after both, and boldly bad him bace,
So ran they all, as they had bene at bace,
To Vna back he cast him to retire;
And back retyrd, his life bloud forth with all did draw.
That halfe the steele behind his back did rest;
And through back wayes, that none might them espy,
And beat them back, whilest many vnderneath him fell.
And from the country back to priuate farmes he scorsed.
And wickedly backbite: Her name men Sclaunder call.
But after them did barke, and still backbite,
Leasings, backbytings, and vaine-glorious crakes,
Of needments at his backe. Thus as they past,
To wish you backe returne with foule disgrace,
Armed to point, sought backe to turne againe;
From turning backe, and forced her to stay:
His grasping hold, and from her turne him backe:
He backe returning by the Yuorie dore,
With that misformed spright he backe returnd againe.
Do backe rebut, and each to other yeeldeth land.
She turning backe with ruefull countenaunce,
For on his backe a heauy load he bare
She backe returned with some labour lost;
To looken backe; his eyes be fixt before.
But both from backe and belly still did spare,
They backe returned to the Princely Place;
And would haue backe retyred to her caue,
Then bowing downe her aged backe, she kist
Thence turning backe in silence soft they stole,
That backe returned without heauenly grace;
And backe returning tooke her wonted way,
And turning backe, gan fast to fly away,
Then backe to fight againe, new breathed and entire.
An yron brest, and backe of scaly bras,
And scaly tayle was stretcht adowne his backe full low.
And chauft, that any on his backe should sit;
That brought not backe the balefull body dead;
Eft looking backe would faine haue runne away;
Against my liking backe, to doe you grace:
He lifted vp his hand, that backe againe did start.
Backe to the world, whose ioyes so fruitlesse are;
And shortly backe returne vnto this place,
Does ouerspred his long bras-scaly backe,
But th'idle stroke yet backe recoyld in vaine,
But backe againe the sparckling steele recoyld,
Behind his backe vnweeting, where he stood,
Into the same the knight backe ouerthrowen, fell.
Perforce rebutted backe. The weapon bright
Backe to returne to that great Faerie Queene,
Ye then shall hither backe returne againe,
Vnto his Farie Queene backe to returne:
To call backe life to her forsaken shop;
But with redoubled buffes them backe did put:
Both fled attonce, ne euer backe returned eie.
And at her backe a bow and quiuer gay,
And low behinde her backe were scattered:
With that she swaruing backe, her Iauelin bright
And pluckt him backe; who all on fire streightway,
And both his hands fast bound behind his backe,
Behind his backe he bore a brasen shield,
But backe rebounding, left the forckhead keene;
Yet being entred, might not backe retyre;
Backe to the strond retyrd, and there still stayd,
Into the world to guide him backe, as he him brought.
So backe againe, him brought to liuing light.
Were fixed at his backe, to cut his ayerie wayes.
Loe where the dreadfull Death behind thy backe doth stond.
Then backe againe turning his busie hond,
Thence backe againe faire Alma led them right,
Into the which returning backe, he fell:
Yet twise they were repulsed backe againe,
And twise renforst, backe to their ships to fly,
Which drawing backe, he looked euermore
That backe againe it did aloft rebownd,
A second fall redoubling backe againe.
Backe to the world, bad liuers to torment:
May backe returne, but is condemned to be drent.
But neither toyle nor trauell might her backe recoyle.
Ne did the other backe his foot returne,
To weet if they would turne backe to that place:
And hold them backe, that would in errour fall;
The word gone out, she backe againe would call,
To this his natiue soyle thou backe shalt bring,
Shall backe repulse the valiaunt Brockwell twise,
Least backe againe the kingdome he from them should beare.
Whiles on his broad round backe they softly slid
So with the Dwarfe he backe return'd againe,
Soone as she Venus saw behind her backe,
Till they againe returne backe by the hinder gate.
She turnd her selfe backe to her wicked leares
